                    <h1><i class="fas fa-question-circle"></i> Frequently Asked Questions</h1>

                    <h2 id="general">General Questions</h2>

                    <h3>What is Monolith Firewall?</h3>
                    <p>
                        Monolith Firewall is an open-source firewall distribution built on .NET 10 and Debian 13.
                        It provides enterprise-grade network security features with an easy-to-use interface, suitable
                        for home users, small businesses, and enterprises.
                    </p>

                    <h3>Is Monolith Firewall really free?</h3>
                    <p>
                        Yes! Monolith Firewall is 100% free and open-source under the MIT License. There are no
                        premium versions, hidden fees, or feature limitations. The entire source code is available
                        on GitHub for anyone to audit, modify, and contribute to.
                    </p>

                    <h3>Why is it built on .NET 10?</h3>
                    <p>
                        .NET 10 provides excellent performance, modern APIs, cross-platform compatibility, and
                        strong security features. It allows us to build a robust, maintainable firewall solution
                        while leveraging the extensive .NET ecosystem.
                    </p>

                    <h3>Can I use this in production?</h3>
                    <p>
                        Yes! Monolith Firewall is designed for production use. However, as with any security software,
                        we recommend thorough testing in your environment before deployment and staying current with updates.
                    </p>

                    <h2 id="installation">Installation Questions</h2>

                    <h3>What hardware do I need?</h3>
                    <p>
                        Minimum requirements are modest: a 64-bit processor (x86_64 or ARM64), 1 GB RAM, 8 GB storage,
                        and at least 2 network interfaces. For better performance, we recommend 2+ GB RAM and an SSD.
                        See the <a asp-page="/Docs/Installation" style="color: var(--primary-color);">Installation Guide</a> for details.
                    </p>

                    <h3>Can I install this on a virtual machine?</h3>
                    <p>
                        Absolutely! Monolith Firewall works great on VirtualBox, VMware, Hyper-V, KVM, and other
                        virtualization platforms. Make sure to configure at least two network adapters (one for WAN,
                        one for LAN) in your VM settings.
                    </p>

                    <h3>Can I install on existing Debian installation?</h3>
                    <p>
                        While technically possible, we recommend using the official ISO for the best experience.
                        The ISO includes all necessary components pre-configured and optimized for firewall use.
                    </p>

                    <h3>How do I update Monolith Firewall?</h3>
                    <p>
                        Updates can be installed through the web interface (<strong>System &gt; Updates</strong>) or
                        via CLI with <code>monolith-cli system update install</code>. We recommend enabling automatic
                        security updates.
                    </p>

                    <h2 id="configuration">Configuration Questions</h2>

                    <h3>I can't access the web interface, what should I do?</h3>
                    <p>Common troubleshooting steps:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Ensure you're connecting from the LAN side, not WAN</li>
                        <li>Verify the firewall's LAN IP address using the console</li>
                        <li>Check if your browser accepts the self-signed SSL certificate</li>
                        <li>Try accessing via HTTP first: <code>http://&lt;firewall-ip&gt;:8080</code></li>
                        <li>Verify network connectivity with <code>ping &lt;firewall-ip&gt;</code></li>
                    </ul>

                    <h3>How do I reset the admin password?</h3>
                    <p>From the console or SSH:</p>
                    <div class="code-block">
                        <code># Reset admin password<br>
monolith-cli user reset-password admin<br>
<br>
# Follow the prompts to set a new password</code>
                    </div>

                    <h3>Can I manage multiple LAN networks?</h3>
                    <p>
                        Yes! Monolith Firewall supports VLANs and multiple LAN interfaces. You can create separate
                        networks for guest WiFi, IoT devices, servers, etc., with different security policies for each.
                    </p>

                    <h3>How do I configure port forwarding?</h3>
                    <p>
                        Navigate to <strong>Firewall &gt; NAT &gt; Port Forward</strong> and add a new rule.
                        Specify the external port, internal IP, and internal port. See the
                        <a asp-page="/Docs/Configuration" style="color: var(--primary-color);">Configuration Guide</a> for details.
                    </p>

                    <h2 id="performance">Performance Questions</h2>

                    <h3>What throughput can I expect?</h3>
                    <p>
                        Performance varies by hardware, but on modest hardware (dual-core CPU, 2 GB RAM), you can
                        typically achieve 500+ Mbps throughput. With dedicated hardware and proper optimization,
                        multi-gigabit throughput is achievable.
                    </p>

                    <h3>Does it support hardware offloading?</h3>
                    <p>
                        Yes! Monolith Firewall supports hardware offloading features like:
                    </p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>TCP/UDP checksum offloading</li>
                        <li>Segmentation offloading (TSO/GSO)</li>
                        <li>Receive-side scaling (RSS)</li>
                    </ul>

                    <h3>How many concurrent connections can it handle?</h3>
                    <p>
                        This depends on available RAM. With 2 GB RAM, you can typically handle 50,000+ concurrent
                        connections. With 4+ GB RAM, hundreds of thousands of connections are possible.
                    </p>

                    <h2 id="security">Security Questions</h2>

                    <h3>How secure is Monolith Firewall?</h3>
                    <p>
                        Security is our top priority. Monolith Firewall is built on Debian 13, a security-focused
                        Linux distribution, and follows security best practices. The open-source nature means the
                        code can be audited by anyone. We regularly release security updates.
                    </p>

                    <h3>Does it include intrusion detection?</h3>
                    <p>
                        Yes! Monolith Firewall includes built-in IDS (Intrusion Detection System) capabilities
                        for real-time threat monitoring and blocking.
                    </p>

                    <h3>Can I use it with my existing VPN?</h3>
                    <p>
                        Yes! Monolith Firewall supports both OpenVPN and WireGuard. You can configure it as a VPN
                        server, client, or both. See the <a asp-page="/Docs/VPN" style="color: var(--primary-color);">VPN Setup Guide</a>.
                    </p>

                    <h3>Does it support IPv6?</h3>
                    <p>
                        Yes! Full IPv6 support is included, with dual-stack IPv4/IPv6 operation.
                    </p>

                    <h2 id="troubleshooting">Troubleshooting</h2>

                    <h3>My internet connection isn't working</h3>
                    <p>Check these common issues:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Verify WAN interface has a valid IP address</li>
                        <li>Check DNS settings (try 8.8.8.8 or 1.1.1.1)</li>
                        <li>Verify NAT is configured and enabled</li>
                        <li>Check firewall rules aren't blocking outbound traffic</li>
                        <li>Test from the firewall itself: <code>ping 8.8.8.8</code></li>
                    </ul>

                    <h3>Devices can't get DHCP addresses</h3>
                    <p>Troubleshooting steps:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Verify DHCP server is enabled on the LAN interface</li>
                        <li>Check DHCP range doesn't conflict with static IPs</li>
                        <li>Ensure firewall rules allow DHCP traffic (UDP ports 67-68)</li>
                        <li>Check DHCP server logs: <code>monolith-cli logs dhcp</code></li>
                    </ul>

                    <h3>High CPU usage</h3>
                    <p>Potential causes and solutions:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Enable hardware offloading if available</li>
                        <li>Reduce logging verbosity</li>
                        <li>Check for bandwidth-intensive applications</li>
                        <li>Review firewall rules for inefficiencies</li>
                        <li>Consider upgrading hardware for higher throughput</li>
                    </ul>

